The paper deals with the privacy-preserving analysis of call detail records (CDRs), which are typically stored in databases (cs.DB). The authors propose a differentially-private method for summarizing CDRs, which is a common technique in privacy-preserving data analysis (cs.CR). The method involves the use of Bloom filters, which are a popular data structure in machine learning and data mining (cs.LG). The paper also discusses experiments conducted on a real-life dataset, which involves the analysis of large amounts of data (cs.SI). Finally, the paper deals with privacy concerns related to the release of sensitive data, which is a common theme in cybersecurity research (cs.CY).
